If your string is simple like this all the time, you could use the java [`Pattern`][1] indeed. But if your strings get more complicated and you want to extract contents from nested structures, you should really use a HTML parser.

For choosing the right parser look at this question: [Which HTML parser is best][2].

If you stay with patterns, your regex will look like this:

    Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile( &quot;&lt;b&gt;(.*?)&lt;/b&gt;&quot; );
    Matcher m = pattern.matcher( &quot;neverMind&lt;b&gt;What is up&lt;/b&gt;neverMind&quot; );
    if( m.find() ) {
        String theStringYouAreLookingFor = m.group( 1 );
    }


  [1]: http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/regex/Pattern.html
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2168610/which-html-parser-is-best

If you want it without matcher

    		String a=&quot;neverMind&lt;b&gt;What is up&lt;/b&gt;neverMind&quot;;
		int index1=a.indexOf(&quot;&gt;&quot;);
		int index2=a.indexOf(&quot;&lt;/b&gt;&quot;);
